column1: 5960159;NFMD_-wFrbfdhTcdHPDCZQ;15;2014-02-06;8;P9hsidWSqjjsz-XJO0KWGw;4;"I have had this place bookmarked for some time
column2: so when given the opportunity to dine here with some fellow Yelpers
column3: I was excited by the prospect. We arrived around noon and the place wasn't too busy. We shared a large number of items from the menu.

column1: Here's a list of all everything we tried:
GARLC KNOTS: Really good. Really small
column2: but warm
column3: flavorful and soft.

column1: RICE BALLS: These were just ok. I enjoyed them
column2: but they weren't notable.

column1: LASAGNA EXPLOSIONS - I don't usually like lasagna
column2: but this was a nice change of pace from typical lasagna. Moist and very cheesy.

column1: TRIPE - My favorite part of the meal. I don't typically enjoy tripe
column2: but this preparation was very enjoyable. Not chewy at all and didn't have that tripe-y smell that usually turns me off.

column1: MEATBALLS & ITALIAN SAUSAGE - This dish was ok. The meatballs are huge
column2: however
column3: and I enjoyed the tomato sauce.

column1: SEAFOOD PASTA IN GARLIC CREAM SAUCE - This dish was just ok. the sauce didn't have enough depth of flavor for me and I don't see myself ordering this dish again if I returned.
SICILIAN PIZZA - I'm not usually a fan of deep dish. This had nice flavor
column2: but it was a little doughy for my taste. Everyone else seemed to love this pizza
column3: so it's just a matter of preference.

column1: WHITE PIZZA - This was one of the standouts. The pizza was seasoned and cooked well. I could have eaten just this dish and been happy.
EGGPLANT PARM - I absolutely love eggplant
column2: but this wasn't my favorite preparation. Too much breading and the eggplant was sliced a little too thinly for my taste. I do enjoy how they serve ziti instead of spaghetti with this dish
column3: since I'm not a fan of spaghetti.

column1: ZEPPOLES - These were my favorite of all the desserts served. I usually don't enjoy Italian desserts since they are a little denser than I prefer
column2: so the zeppoles stood out for being a little more subtle and not overly sweet. Plus
column3: I can never resist powdered sugar.

column1: RAINBOW CAKE - This was a little on the dry side for me. A little too chocolatey as well
column2: but that's just a matter of preference.

column1: CANNOLI - I don't usually like cannolis and I can't say this one changed my mind about them.
ASSORTED COOKIES - These were good. They have a number of varieties and I would be back for more of these for sure.
Service was spectacular. Our drinks were kept full and everyone was extremely friendly and entertaining
column2: making our meal that much more enjoyable.

column1: We all had a great meal and there were plenty of leftovers for all. I was able to take some home to my mom who's a pasta fanatic and she loved it. I'd definitely be back for pizza
column2: tripe and dessert as those were my favorites from our meal.";18;UYcmGbelzRa0Q6JqzLoguw

column1: Initially

column1: Ironically enough

3772073;KBGoTNvOoV3ixc8zaaMHnw;7;2016-07-19;5;eqWQ7VfM0rlBSJpPNmbOrw;3;"I drove here with high expectations of hopefully receiving authentic British Isles fish and chips.
Fish?
Basically three fancy fish sticks and not the long solid piece of beer battered cod or haddock that I was expecting or what one would receive in the UK.
Chips? (Fries to us Americans)
Slim cut French fries and nothing more. These were not the proper steak type chips found in the UK. They also weren't cooked properly
column2: meaning they weren't golden brown and crispy. They also were not cooked in beef fat like they would do in the UK. Beef fat = lard or Crisco. This is what McDonald's does and we all know that Mickey D's has the most highly regarded FF in the fast food industry. This is the reason why.

column1: In the UK it is generally accepted that malt vinegar and then salt is added to ones chips. I did the same with the chips that I received
column2: but they were so limp that they didn't absorb the malt vinegar. FAIL!

column1: Coleslaw?
My side was automatically coleslaw. The traditional side in the UK is mushy peas
column2: which is on their menu. I'm sorry that I didn't get to try this
column3: because I've never had them before. Sadly
column4: I wasn't given the option.

column1: Tartar sauce? Very good.
Beer? Harp. Ice cold and very good. THE best thing on the table.
Service? Cheerful and friendly. Very good.
Price? Entree and beer + tip = $20. The entree itself was a little more expensive than Long John Silvers and half as good. I was expecting better.
I'm sure that there are some excellent items on the menu that I need to try
column2: but my ""toe in the water"" test of the food was pretty much underwhelming. I may go back to try some of the other traditional items
column3: but it won't be anytime soon. There are plenty of other British Isles restaurants to sample first.";8;4FE8md9fMr_jZFNbcOmHsQ

1237471;SMPbvZLSMMb7KU76YNYMGg;0;2018-06-19;0;fkOPXt9FEr3a7g2x0sXoLA;2;"AWKWARD would be the best way to describe our stay. Let me start by saying the hotel appeared clean and the room was nice but just about everything else that possibly could have gone wrong did.

Upon check in we were told that the systems were down and given our key any way. We arrived at our room and noticed the bar/snacks weren't fully restocked but other than that the room appeared clean so we thought nothing of it and got ready for our night.

This is where it gets weird: we come back to our hotel around 4AM to find out that we've been locked out of our room because our key card no longer works! This was our first night! So we went down to the front desk only to find out that they apparently never checked us in and were under the impression that some one else was in our room and she asked if we had been inside the room yet and when we replied ""yes and our stuff is already in there too"" at that point she called her manager (she seemed just as concerned as we were to be honest). After some confusion and about 10 mins of panic
column2: we were able to get a new room key and finally make it to our room. The lady at the front desk had absolutely no clue what went wrong and was under the impression that some one else was staying in our room. I can't even express how unprofessional that was
column3: not that I'm blaming her she did do her best and was very polite. She gave us a complimentary late check out but that didn't really give us back our sleep lost that morning.

column1: So fast forward about 3-4 hours: we get woken up at around 9 AM by some one trying to take our room service table back when we hadn't even called them to pick it up. We were asleep and an employee legit walked in to the room with out our consent. My friend had to get up and tell them that we will call them when we want it removed LIKE THE SIGN SAYS TO DO.
We spent the rest of our stay hanging out at our friends hotels (Cesar's
column2: Venetian) and had a great time. Too bad our own hotel was so STRANGE or we would have actually spent money there but we literally went to every casino near by except ours because we didn't trust all their system failures.

column1: ***We also had Father's Day breakfast at the aria cafe which was honestly the only reason my stay didn't absolutely suck and I will absolutely write a separate review for them in the near future. It was great!! Clean
column2: bright
column3: pretty
column4: great food
column5: fantastic server
column6: awesome drinks. Literally the only reason aria gets 2 stars instead of one.

column1: And then our last morning we get woken up by a family sitting in the hallway. I opened the door to ask them to keep it down and that's when I found out they were in the same situation as us the other night
column2: locked out of their room due to a system malfunction. Really Aria? ALL WEEKEND?? Might wanna consider changing OS
column3: Dell is clearly screwing you up left and right lol.

column1: So upon leaving we stopped by guest services to address our complaints and inform them that several other things went wrong after being locked out. I asked for a manager and the attendant passed me her phone and says ""listen to this
column2: our system is down"" ......there was no dial tone. Meaning their system had been down the whole time we were there. 4 days. It even appeared that the staff was fed up with the hotels mishaps at this point. They were all very honest and courteous which I did truly appreciate
column3: but I don't think I'll be doing business with Aria or any MGM hotel in the future
column4: seeing our friend also had a horrible experience at the bellagio (which is supposed to be MGM's more high-end hotel/casino. NOPE). I'm truly disappointed because I had a ton of Mlife points. But I guess WE will have no choice but to bring our business else where next time. I told my friend to stop spending money at mgm and we spent our last day at the Venetian and had a blast. The MGM group really needs to be more on point or they will lose a ton of business
column5: I witnessed MANY guests being inconvenienced this weekend. I know for a fact it wasn't just us.

column1: To avoid wasting further time I grabbed the assistant front desk managers business card and will attempt to follow up with them and will UPDATE MY REVIEW with their response.
If any of the staff are reading
column2: you were all very nice and I'm sorry you have to put up with such nonsense
column3: please consider leaving Aria for a more respectable resort that doesn't force you to bullshit people all the time.";2;bB57eksdXQDrQY16rRHGRQ

3283716;X-WXPGYuuknAjZkpYGeRiw;2;2017-01-25;3;_8RYxX2WVPNOPKFWapR7JA;3;"Came here for a Exposition for the past three days. Also in the past I've been here for the same expo so I figured I would share my experience. There are mannnnnyyyy suites available. There are almost about 30 buildings with a plethora of rooms and suites. Each place is labeled with what building you are in order so you can find it.

Many pools there and cool courtyards. So when you have down time it's a great place to sit relax and unwind. Rooms are really priced great. Very spacious rooms some even with an upstairs. Not all rooms have an amazing view but some actually do. Rooms are kinda out dated but still nice. In a few years I will see this place remodeling to hopefully catch up with the (room) times.
Staff was friendly. From front desk to house keeping. Rooms looked great after house cleaning
column2: plus they are very nice when you ask them to come back later to clean. Front desk was helpful when the keys deactivated twice and when I had questions about what food to eat in the area that's close even though I'm a local they helped me out.

column1: This hotel is walking distance from food like checkers
column2: subway and a taco shop. Plus across the street is the hard rock hotel. Easy walk to the casino. If you are staying for a convention or just visiting it's a cool spot. Family oriented too. Don't expect over the top luxury but expect nice hospitality with ok rooms!";2;ugpGI6jgFq_gDyaGBn1Cmw

column1: 2621272;knU0b5FaqtUSr1UrflaVbg;0;2018-03-26;0;TtjwaZDWBnek3C-DabwdxA;5;"I don't take the time to write many reviews
column2: but my experience here was just that amazing that I'm feeling compelled to! I had seen ads for Luv and found that I really liked a lot of the dress options so I decided that I would make an appointment about 5 days in advance when I found out my mom would be in town. They were very friendly on the phone and made me an appointment on the day that I wanted. I was then emailed a questionnaire to fill out so that they could get a better idea of what I was looking for.

column1: The shop itself is quite beautiful and there is a large selection of dresses
column2: but it's not overwhelming! We were immediately greeted by our coordinator Katie (holy crap she was amazing) and we're offered water
column3: coffee
column4: and snacks. From the moment Katie shook my hand she was extremely welcoming and made sure to listen to everything that I was thinking that I wanted. We looked through every dress and I picked out ones that I thought I'd like and Katie also picked a few that she thought would be worth trying as well.

column1: By the time we got to the back to start trying all of these amazing gowns on
column2: I felt so comfortable being myself around Katie that it made the experience so easy and so fun. The first dress that I tried on was Katie's pick and it was the dress that I ultimately chose! I tried on all of the other gowns and when it came down to 2
column3: I was allowed to take my time trying on each one back and forth until finally it clicked for me which dress was ""the one"".

column1: I ended up spending about 30 minutes longer than my appointment making my final decision and Katie was by my side and not rushing me whatsoever. It was an emotional experience for everyone
column2: including myself when I had the whole look put together and I couldn't have asked for anything more. I'm counting down the days until I can go back and plan my alterations with them! Thanks Luv Bridal!";0;C-qDvuiPEvjAqoKfDZibBg

::Food::

The Roasted Jalapeo Poppers were presented on a long narrow tray with small shot glasses. Each glass contained a white creamy flavorful sauce and one crunchy breaded jalapeno popper. They were not very spicy but we were warned that one contained a fiery surprise.  Inside was cheddar cheese
column2: jalapeno
column3: and cheddar ranch; the temperature was perfect. We thought there would only be one fiery surprise but I think we got two.  My tongue was burning and my nose was running;  it wasn't extremely hot but it was hot.  It was fun trying to guess which one had the fiery surprise. My Uber Cheeseburger was grilled over apple and alder wood.  It had Fontina cheese
column4: raclette

column6: it had chocolate hazelnut pudding
column7: coffee shake
column8: and praline cookie. The combination of all the flavors tasted good.

column1: 1842408;ohEnmKpF7i2_ujme1p_vUQ;0;2010-06-12;0;Nfq4QqM81UyACeIoCEXq3g;5;"So without a single notion of what a Pasty actually was
column2: I joined my usual ""Find unique and interesting places to eat"" group of friends to try this place out.  And boy am I glad I did.

column1: We took a seat at the bar that overlooked the kitchen and I started off with a 20oz glass of one of my favorite wheat beers; Hoegaarden.
As we sat there watching one of the employees make a batch of Pasties
column2: my friends and I chatted casually with himself and a few other employees about the place and what was good to eat and such.

column1: Being adventurous I decided to try out one of the many veggie menu items and went with the Chicken Basil and Pesto Pasty.  It featured vegetarian chicken and I was curious as to how it would stack up against the real thing.
It was served quite prettily shortly after we ordered and I dug in.  Delicious!  The veggie chicken obviously wasn't a dead ringer for the real deal
column2: but I felt it worked quite flawlessly with the rest of the contents of the dish.

column1: After that we decided on different desserts and I chose the chocolate rum bread pudding.  It was different than any bread pudding I've ever had for starters because it was chocolate.  Next it had a crunchy outer shell that contained the gooey goodness inside.  I was informed that they were sadly out of the vanilla drizzle that normally accompanies it as well
column2: so that would have also made it unique had they not been out.

column1: It's also worth noting that the employees were an absolute blast to interact with as they were playing quirky and fun songs off their iPod and were just being outgoing and fun in general.  It was mentioned though that the manager was not there at the time and that usually had the place had more patrons (there were maybe 2 other couples in the place) in it they would have had to conform to more ""professional"" standards.
Overall it's a shame I live so far from the place because I could easily see myself becoming a regular.  Prices after pasty
column2: dessert and 2 20oz beers and tip was just around 27 if I remember correctly.";0;6fjsqDqQU6-Jsue9Gd9YTg

column1: 5755465;OBG1j517k7aZRNC1HAL0TA;2;2012-01-21;0;fObXM8Gdn0iob1tHvhlSJQ;4;"Previously

column1: I remember really enjoying the bread last time
column2: and this time was no different. The bread was warm and spongy in the center. We asked for some butter in addition to the olive oil and balsamic vinegar

column4: it was a little hard to flag down our server.

column1: My boyfriend started with an insalata di Fabbrica with romaine hearts

column3: toasted focaccia. From the description
column4: I imagined this to be similar to a Caesar salad. I appreciated that the dressing was tangier and lighter

column1: The salad was followed by tortiglioni with oven baked Fabbrica meatball
column2: tomato and buffalo mozzarella. This came out as a stunning casserole of cheese-topped baked pasta

column1: I pointed at menu item # 15: Bun Dac Biet. Kay picked #16: Bun Cha Gio.

column2: shrimp

column5: carrot
column6: noodles

column1: Kay's meal was very similar to mine. Watching her do so was a delight in itself. I like to watch my girl eat for some bizarre reason. Fetish? You tell me.

I THINK I have finally achieved a sort of competence with chopsticks. The key lies in clearing your mind while you're using them and training the muscles in your fingers to do things they aren't used to doing. My circumstances this evening caused me to learn something I never thought I'd be able to do at all; the equivalent of having to hang glide from a cliff to dodge a stampede of dinosaurs.
We got our check ($22)
column2: paid it
column3: and hustled back across the street to Altar in time to catch the back half of the 3rd opener's set
column4: our bellies warm and full

column1: Ramen Hashi

column1: Noodles - everyday Sun noodle variety.  Toothsome

column3: machine made noodles.

column1: Broth - Basic tonkotsu.  Not heavily extracted but a good porky flavor
column2: good amount of gelatin

column4: slightly sweet soy added.  Agreeable.  The shio and shoyu broths are both chicken based.  Not very little extraction and almost no collagen.  Clean.

column1: Toppings - Well made

column1: Basic service.  Quick with food taking five minutes from order to table.  Perfect.
If nothing's wrong
column2: why not a higher rating?  I've had better.  The baseline in Hawaii includes shops straight from Japan.  Use of multi kinds of flour to make noodles

column5: this is still plenty good and will probably satisfy most any ramen craving.";37;oeAhRa8yFa9jtrhaHnOyxQ

column1: Update:  Before going to see them please read up on atypical moles.  1 in 10 people have them.  I have provided a link below. column1: 105360;AV6weBrZFFBfRGCbcRGO4g;0;2014-10-18;4;7jnbnxniqzfKjyKexKOeBQ;2;"Here's an interesting comparison:
Wife & I had a business conference in Las Vegas
column2: decided to also spend a few days at one of our favorite natural earth wonders
column3: Zion National Park
column4: about 3 hours from Vegas.

column1: The hotel in the tiny Zion Park town of Springdale honored our reservation for a king-bed room
column2: which included a fridge
column3: coffee/tea/hotpot
column4: a full room service menu
column5: an ample complimentary breakfast each morning
column6: and full wi-fi. There's about 15 brand-name and mom-&-pop hotels in the little town outside the park
column7: and all of them offer the same.

column1: After 3 days in Zion
column2: checked into the Luxor
column3: a name raising expectations of something ""deluxe
column4: on the ultra-modern
column5: high-end-deluxe-hotels Las Vegas Strip. Not so much...

column1: Oversold
column2: can't give us the king room we reserved
column3: gotta take queen instead. OK. Fridge in room? Nah. Coffee/tea/hotpot? Nope. Comp breakfast? Whadya think this is
column4: the Ritz?

column1: How 'bout in-room Wi-Fi
column2: gotta have Wi-Fi?

column1: Er
column2: nope. We've got a long Ethernet cable for hardwire connection
column3: but that's useless for our iPads. Wait...what century is this? A marquee hotel on the ultra-modern Las Vegas Strip
column4: with every kind of digital & neon connection available - hell
column5: even the Luxor pyramid lights up in sequence at night - and no Wi-Fi in the rooms?! ""Well we have Wi-Fi in the public areas
column6: down at the casinos & restaurants."" Ahh
column7: there's the tip off...

column1: As confirmed by my wife and several other Vegas-savvy people (I'm a little slow about corporate manipulation
column2: ) the reason they don't have any of these basic in-room amenities is because THEY DONT WANT YOU TO STAY IN YOUR ROOM. Not even for a half-hour
column3: enjoying a hot teas while researching tonight's restaurant on the Web. They want you downstairs
column4: gambling and buying your coffee or tea at one of the 6 Starbucks. Pure corporate manipulation put before comfort first.

column1: There have been close to 2000 reviews over many years for this place
column2: and they can never raise above 2-1/2 stars. You get the distinct impression they've done nothing to spruce up the place or invest in better pay for their employees or basic amenities for the rooms. And
column3: talking to the staff
column4: you get the feeling they really don't give a toss
column5: because they know the hotel will stay constantly booked anyway
column6: whether they upgrade or not. Vegas don't care 'bout you
column7: just your wallet.";12;W0mBfIE1la_OLSouckloZg

column1: 1156047;Wxxvi3LZbHNIDwJ-ZimtnA;0;2016-03-03;2;xlHEXEEjnn2vYTEl0K1orw;1;"One of the worst hotel experiences I have ever had - their customer experience is the very antithesis of the Ritz-Carlton. Came here for a conference and they were out of nonsmoking rooms so first offered to bring me an air purifier and move me to another room the following day
column2: then offered to upgrade me to a higher-level suite for an extra $100/night. Why they couldn't give me a complimentary upgrade the way airlines sometimes do if they're sold out of coach seats is beyond me - clearly they were uninterested in any future stays by me. That was unacceptable to me so the manager somehow found a nonsmoking room that hadn't been listed in inventory.

column1: After I spent some time outside and came back to the room
column2: I realized why - it smelled like smoke - faint
column3: but definitely there. By the time I came to that realization
column4: I was too tired to deal with it so called the front desk and asked them to bring in an air purifier in the morning. When I went back to my room around noon to check on the situation
column5: it was clear the air purifier had done nothing to help with the smell
column6: so I requested to be moved to another room. They didn't have anything available right then but told me they would put something on hold for me as soon as something became available. I told them I wouldn't be ready to change rooms until later that night because I was working and they said that was fine. Got a voicemail later that afternoon that a room would be held for me but only till 5
column7: so I had to call the front desk again (and by the way
column8: every time I called the front desk it was a 5-10 minute wait on hold) and request that it be held until 6:30
column9: which was the earliest I could get there. They had to have a 2-minute sidebar with their manager before they said it was fine. Apparently none of these people are empowered to satisfy customers by themselves
column10: nor are the managers allowed to interact with customers directly
column11: since this sidebar occurred every time there was a problem.

column1: When I came to the front desk to get the hotel key for my new room
column2: they couldn't find anything at first. Another sidebar with the manager. Then when I asked to assess the new room before I checked out of the old room
column3: another sidebar to get permission. Once I made a decision
column4: I had to call the front desk (another 10-minute wait on hold). Are you getting the idea?

column1: Fortunately
column2: the new room smelled much better than the old room
column3: so I did move my belongings. The shower in the new room
column4: unfortunately
column5: ran from barely tepid to not quite hot enough with the dial cranked all the way to the left
column6: but by this time I had learned not to expect any sort of customer service
column7: so I didn't even bother reporting it.

column1: Needless to say
column2: I will not voluntarily stay here if I ever come back to Vegas.";6;O1owVDyKZH312d7ajr2M3A

column2: but Le Pho was easy to find

column4: but at least we were able to park close by!

column1: The spot is clean and open

column1: As for the entrees:

column3: and practically falling off the bone.  It was really good.

column1: I had opted for the rib-eye pho

column3: there was a TON of rib-eye meat in it
column4: the noodles were cooked perfectly
column5: and the addition of herbs and sriracha helped me to spice some of the sickness out. I actually have left overs for lunch today.

column1: All in all
column2: I was very pleased with our visit.   Service was great
column3: and the food was phenomenal.  We both had 2 huge bowls of pho

column3: I wasn't listening to him introducing himself and his co-worker that was gonna take care of us. I think that's awesome they partnered up their servers at this restaurant
column4: they can be on top of things. But anyway they bring out dinner rolls. They look like normal dinner rolls with sea salt sprinkled on top. I buttered it up and took a bite
column5: it was a little toasty on the outside and so soft on the inside and oh my that salt goes so well with the roll. I didn't want to eat anymore because I knew I was gonna get full but I did anyway haha. We ordered the Hama Hama oysters and there were a few condiment. It was amazing and so fresh. We wanted to order another half dozen but didn't. We also ordered a Caesar salad
column6: i didn't care too much for it. My scallops were cooked perfect! And my husband's domestic wagyu was like butter and phenomenal! We also got the whipped potatoes (delicious!) and risotto (okay). Souffl was yummy and they also gave my husband a complimentary dessert for his birthday. It was a panna cotta with berries.. That was amazing!! Definitely wanna come back! If you want an wonderful experience
column7: come here!!;0;iYSAOmjHvsz01yXW612Gaw
